d manuscripts, theses\/dissertations, government reports, preprints, etc.). <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1199494,"guid":"2D050350D29711EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","previous_id":1199493,"previous_guid":"F6F56710D29511EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"3EA45CB3F04C40B6A64581D70324D028","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Find major ion composition of the freshwater body"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"5B6B969AF04E46BB9CB16A79D5527FF1","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Convert the concentrations of the elements to mg\/L from \u00b5M if the data is not already in this format.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1199496,"guid":"7EF82B60D29711EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","previous_id":1199494,"previous_guid":"2D050350D29711EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"A7452DE2AE4D4DBCB469D2156D90B1D7","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Create the formulation of the major ion solution"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"78CCB132642644B8926704AB390E5DED","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Download Freshwater_Major_Ion_Solution_calculation.csv from Zenodo at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"http:\/\/www.doi.org\/10.5281\/zenodo.5019969\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">http:\/\/www.doi.org\/10.5281\/zenodo.5019969.<\/span><\/a><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dvedbhaz7.jpg\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"9ADB8D6A55D44452A8147C484D263ED3","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dvedbhaz7.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1199497,"guid":"93B465A0D29711EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","previous_id":1199522,"previous_guid":"D1D83BC0D2A811EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"486DE4D5AFF04B45A9242FCA1FE30083","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Create the major ion solution"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"04DB1E79DA2144529220E280DE0C338C","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Add approximately 1\/20 of your total desired volume of distilled water to your intended container for the major ion solution. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Example: use a 20 L carboy to create 20 L of major ion solution and use graduated cylinders for volumetric measurements.  <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1199498,"guid":"4904DED0D29811EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","previous_id":1199497,"previous_guid":"93B465A0D29711EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"AD01759AE2EE48D5BB4B6C357869DAE5","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Create the major ion solution"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"81493E367F57499AB0C75454CD56E0C8","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Add in the Na<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">2<\/span><span>SiO<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">3<\/span><span>x9H<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">2<\/span><span>O, CaCl<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">2<\/span><span>x2H<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">2<\/span><span>O, MgSO<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">4<\/span><span>x7H<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">2<\/span><span>O, Na<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">2<\/span><span>SO<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">4<\/span><span>, and K<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">2<\/span><span>SO<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">4<\/span><span> in concentrations calculated in Step 6 to the distilled water in the major ion solution container.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1199499,"guid":"DF8F3B20D29811EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","previous_id":1199498,"previous_guid":"4904DED0D29811EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"BCCC699DE4004D4B9F2107C39FFAFE34","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Create the major ion solution"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"18BEF834DF9E4EEF9594F0D4BD55F544","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Fill your container to your desired volume using distilled water. Mix the container until all of the salts dissolve. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1199521,"guid":"CF5D29A0D2A811EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","previous_id":1199496,"previous_guid":"7EF82B60D29711EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"6559B7EAF2DC47C8BCE88C020DC822E1","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Create the formulation of the major ion solution"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"07C14AD3803F4A09B23BEC737A4BD9DB","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Fill in the mg\/L box in the with the values calculated from Steps 1 and 2. The box to add this data is highlighted in purple in the image below.<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dvehbhaz7.jpg\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"13972F05D2F7431E9F725167FF2BD89C","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dvehbhaz7.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1199522,"guid":"D1D83BC0D2A811EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","previous_id":1199523,"previous_guid":"D4EEF1A0D2A811EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"226567011E054C0FB2C45199FAED31CB","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Create the formulation of the major ion solution"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"EF97623FBCE3487292CB37A2AD70B953","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">The concentrations to use when creating a major ion solution are in the MIS Recipe box at the bottom of the document. The recipes are highlighted below. Example is the same as in Step 5.<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dvembhaz7.jpg\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"B912E11EA42F45CBB019FDACC9C4C798","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dvembhaz7.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1199523,"guid":"D4EEF1A0D2A811EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","previous_id":1199521,"previous_guid":"CF5D29A0D2A811EB83D6EDF93F3C13BB","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"0320B60EAC274DF7BC42C7C20846BA3B","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Create the formulation of the major ion solution"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"103EF53E33934A3F905C2C606C612339","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>As multiple compounds contribute to the Na<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">+<\/span><span> and SO<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;vertical-align:sub;\">4<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">2-<\/span><span> concentrations and Cl<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">-<\/span><span> concentrations come from Ca<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">2+<\/span><span> calculations, check to make sure that the concentrations are not magnitudes off compared to the reference. There is natural variability in the ionic composition of freshwater systems so some deviation is not an issue. The orange and blue highlights under final concentration column show the corresponding compounds between the cations and anions. If the values are several magnitudes off, use the values calculated using the anions. See the example below to see how this works.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">The example used in the image below is for the upper Neuse River Estuary as reported in Paerl and Bowles (1987) from USGS data (Harned 1982).<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">References:<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Harned, D.A., 1982. <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Water quality of the Neuse River, North Carolina-Variability, pollution loads, and long-term trends<\/span><span> (USGS Report No. 2185-D). USGPO,.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Paerl, H.W. and Bowles, N.D., 1987. Dilution bioassays: Their application to assessments of nutrient limitation in hypereutrophic waters. <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Hydrobiologia<\/span><span>, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">146<\/span><span>(3), pp.265-273. <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1007\/BF00016348\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1007\/BF00016348<\/span><\/a><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dverbhaz7.jpg\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"47DA923769D54DA684E0A86DA1D54CA5","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dverbhaz7.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Several experimental designs require serial dilutions of site water. To perform dilutions without the use of prefiltered water or without the addition of nutrients and trace metals in freshwater systems, major ion solutions (MIS) are required. MIS provides a nutrient and metal free dilution medium to minimize hypertonic and hypotonic effects on the organisms in the samples during dilutions by balancing major dissolved ions of Ca<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">2+<\/span><span>, Mg<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">2+<\/span><span>, Na<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">+<\/span><span>, K<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">+<\/span><span>, Cl<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">-<\/span><span>, SO<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;vertical-align:sub;\">4<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">2-<\/span><span>, and Si<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">4+<\/span><span> in freshwater systems. MIS are the equivalent of no nutrient artificial sea water for use in freshwater systems. Unlike artificial sea water, MIS formulation for use in freshwater systems changes from site to site. This protocol describes the process of creating a site specific major ion solution from results of elemental analysis data for use in the specified freshwater system.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1624494684}